[{'created': '2020-05-13 00:29:45.000000000', 'message': 'Fix hacking min version to 3.0.1

flake8 new release 3.8.0 added new checks and gate pep8
job start failing. hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to
avoid bringing in a new version with new checks.

Though it is fixed in latest hacking but 2.0 and 3.0 has cap for
flake8 as <4.0.0 which mean flake8 new version 3.9.0 can also
break the pep8 job if new check are added.

To avoid similar gate break in future, we need to bump the hacking min
version.

- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014828.html

Change-Id: I931ffdb03ea55047439d019ccb8a1493b56f2569
'}]
commit_message:
Fix hacking min version to 3.0.1

flake8 new release 3.8.0 added new checks and gate pep8
job start failing. hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to
avoid bringing in a new version with new checks.

Though it is fixed in latest hacking but 2.0 and 3.0 has cap for
flake8 as <4.0.0 which mean flake8 new version 3.9.0 can also
break the pep8 job if new check are added.

To avoid similar gate break in future, we need to bump the hacking min
version.

- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014828.html

Change-Id: I931ffdb03ea55047439d019ccb8a1493b56f2569

[{'created': '2020-01-28 02:13:53.000000000', 'message': 'WIP do all serialization in the expose decorator

Instead of delegating to the @wsme.wsexpose decorator, bring the
required logic into this decorator, including a mimimum required
tojson function.

It may be obvious now that my plan for removing WSME involves copying
just enough of it into ironic, so we need to have the conversation
about whether this is desirable :)

This git branch finishes with WSME removed. Here are some stats
about lines of code (not including unit tests, calculated with cloc):
4500 wsme/wsme
6000 ironic/ironic/api master
7000 ironic/ironic/api story/1651346

In words, we need 1000 out of 4500 lines of WSME source in order to
support 6000 lines of ironic specific API code.

Switching to a replacement for WSME would likely touch a
good proportion of the 6000 lines of ironic specific API code. I
think it would be more practical if the thing it is replacing is
inside the ironic source tree to allow for a gradual transition. So
this approach could be an end in itself, or it could be a step towards
the final goal.

This change is WIP until there is concensus to go with this approach,
and until there are unit tests.

Change-Id: I96661570d77ecb641b4ac7508e65bd7ca83194a5
Story: 1651346

commit_message:
Do all serialization in the expose decorator

Instead of delegating to the @wsme.wsexpose decorator, bring the
required logic into this decorator, including a mimimum required
tojson function.

Change-Id: I96661570d77ecb641b4ac7508e65bd7ca83194a5
Story: 1651346

I know this is WIP, but a couple of comments:
1. There are three different things going on in this patch; changing the devstack plugin, adding the ability to build an amp image, and updating the amphora agent code. Can we split these out?
2. We have moved away from having distro specific elements to having elements that work with all of the distributions. Can we please merge the opensuse changes into the existing amphora-agent and haproxy elements? Ping me if you have questions on how to do that.
3. Do we really need to put in a permanent ifcfg-o-hm0 file on the devstack hosts? It seems like that would be annoying on reboots after devstack has been shutdown.'}, {'account_id': 7016, 'date': '2018-10-17 21:41:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
redfish: handle hardware that is unable to set persistent boot

Some hardware has dropped support for continuous boot, see this thread:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-April/014543.html

Work around by falling back to one-time boot device, restoring it on
every reboot or power on.

Story: #2007527
Task: #39320
Change-Id: I762056dea4f7b8ccdb8f95b2f21e26b45763905d
(cherry picked from commit 18a8e2f6e9d80a827acba39a6ace366c13d40e31)

variable for the ovsdb_connection to using an instance variable.
This means we have to override several different methods/properties.
This could be simplified in ovsdbapp by making ovsdb_connection a
property, which in ovsdbapp access a class variable, and in neutron
it is overridden to to store on the instance, so there would be
less to override.

ovsdbapp is adding user-definable indexed columns so things like
lookups by name will be faster. Due to the way it is architected,
the place to generate the indexes would be just before the
connection starts. Since methods like start_connection are
classmethods in ovsdbapp, and instance methods in neutron, this is
hard to do cleanly w/o ovsdb_connection being a property. Without

commit_message:
Set class ovsdb_conection to None

We override ovsdbapp's Backend class to change from using a class
variable for the ovsdb_connection to using an instance variable.
This means we have to override several different methods/properties.
This could be simplified in ovsdbapp by making ovsdb_connection a
property, which in ovsdbapp access a class variable, and in neutron
it is overridden to to store on the instance, so there would be
less to override.

ovsdbapp is adding user-definable indexed columns so things like
lookups by name will be faster. Due to the way it is architected,
the place to generate the indexes would be just before the
connection starts. Since methods like start_connection are
classmethods in ovsdbapp, and instance methods in neutron, this is
hard to do cleanly w/o ovsdb_connection being a property. Without
this change, neutron would fail if that property was defined. With
the change, it should pass with both old and new code.

Change-Id: Idd184807de24c79dd892046f01e3acdd1168ca2d

commit_message:
Treat endpoints with trailing slashes the same way as without them

We've been historically using endpoints without trailing slashes in
our API. Apparently, some libraries (like gophercloud) are quite
opinionated about it (see the story), so let's handle both.

The implementation could be simpler if we just added trailing slash
to all routes, but it would cause redirects for current users.

Change-Id: Icbd971a8e792f93f9c3fa66ba29bec055dcdee32
Story: #2007660
Task: #39749

commit_message:
Wrap lvm commands in try: except:

Due to the additional of the cinder storage, it's possible that the
log_lvm_info() commands gets called really early before lvm has been
configured.  This wraps the call to pvscan and logs if it doesn't
complete -- the command is just to log the state of lvm at that point.

Also, defensively wrap the reduce_lvm_volume_group_missing() calls for
the same reason.

Closes-Bug: #1878227
Change-Id: I217f62d3f620992d1b18475ca5c3031da9428828

commit_message:
Only notify nova of port status changes if configured

Although notify_nova_on_port_status_changes defaults to true, it
could be to false, making the nova_notifier attribute unsafe to
use without checking.

This patch checks both the config option and that the attribute
exists, since the config could be changed after the plugin is
already initialized without the nova_notifier attribute being set.

Change-Id: Ide0f93275e60dffda10b7da59f6d81c5582c3849
Closes-bug: #1843269
(cherry picked from commit ab4320edb4661f74465ec49166f8d35b8216035f)

commit_message:
Only notify nova of port status changes if configured

Although notify_nova_on_port_status_changes defaults to true, it
could be to false, making the nova_notifier attribute unsafe to
use without checking.

This patch checks both the config option and that the attribute
exists, since the config could be changed after the plugin is
already initialized without the nova_notifier attribute being set.

Change-Id: Ide0f93275e60dffda10b7da59f6d81c5582c3849
Closes-bug: #1843269
(cherry picked from commit ab4320edb4661f74465ec49166f8d35b8216035f)

Would like mdbooth to look at this given the image cache implications.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-06-07 18:45:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: -Code-Review

Sounds like we might give a week exception to this so we can get some others to look at this to determine if it's the direction we'd want to go, and if the extension point mechanism is still needed for this, which it might not be, i.e. if you're using a non-rbd image backend, but nova.conf is configured for ceph stuff in the libvirt driver, we could just check for images from ceph if they aren't in the cache."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-06-07 18:48:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Conversation from IRC today:

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-nova/%23openstack-nova.2018-06-07.log.html#t2018-06-07T17:58:50'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2018-06-07 18:55:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(2 comments)

I would like to get a read on this from someone who understands the image cache code (i.e. mdbooth) before we slam it in. Definitely agree that from a high level this makes sense and we should do it.'}, {'account_id': 1004, 'date': '2018-06-07 19:19:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-06-07 21:02:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(4 comments)

I'm generally in favour of this if we can decide where the code should live.

I wonder if we shouldn't be poking glance's cinder backend for this instead, though. It's marked experimental, but we *could* implement host-attach for ceph if it's not already there. It would be more flexible than a ceph-only optimisation."}, {'account_id': 10338, 'date': '2018-06-11 15:24:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(8 comments)

I am very interested in this. We have a custom "nova.image.download" driver that is a mere 50 LOC and it makes a huge difference in performance in certain workloads, where a new image is built and immediately used on many compute hosts that haven't had the chance to cache it yet.

I can also propose our implementation using the now-deprecated nova.image.download module as PoC. It's using Python Ceph bindings, not `rbd export` though.'}, {'account_id': 28397, 'date': '2018-06-11 15:39:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-10-23 18:49:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I'm not sure what we're waiting on, if anything, with this spec. Maybe waiting for mnaser to come back around it, but at least two people have expressed an interest in using something generic for faster rbd image download. The spec would have to be re-targeted to stein at this point, but beyond that I'm not sure what else we need - maybe more operator input from ceph deployments saying this would be useful to them? Maybe that could be floating around the operators list again, or an ops meetup, or the public cloud SIG during the Stein Forum? I know vexxhost and city network is using ceph."}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2018-10-23 19:38:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I think the use case here makes sense and I'm +1 on adding ceph direct download functionality. But I think we should just add it to the rbd imagebackend instead of preserving the extension point.

So -1 for only the extension point part of this spec. I'd rather update this spec to describe adding direct download into the rbd imagebackend."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2018-10-24 15:28:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I think we need to decide whether or not we're going to un-deprecate an external plugin interface just so we can add this in as an in-tree plugin, or whether or not the functionality gets integrated more directly.

The plugin plumbing (which is currently deprecated) definitely sits in front of the regular code and just bails on the regular paths if the download succeeds via the plugin. Since ceph is a pretty common use-case, and a low-latency local-disk hypervisor configuration would also be common, it seems weird to have this was-external-but-now-in-tree plugin type behavior for what should be something we can just do natively."}, {'account_id': 26458, 'date': '2020-02-10 13:31:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Add spec for downloading images via RBD

This spec adds details on the changes needed to allow nova the ability
to download Glance images into the libvirt image cache via a direct RBD
download instead of over the Glance HTTP API.

Change-Id: Icfcdf203ccce16f417ae043d71381f344e0feaaa
Blueprint: nova-image-download-via-rbd

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-05-13 00:29:46.000000000', 'message': 'Fix hacking min version to 3.0.1

flake8 new release 3.8.0 added new checks and gate pep8
job start failing. hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to
avoid bringing in a new version with new checks.

Though it is fixed in latest hacking but 2.0 and 3.0 has cap for
flake8 as <4.0.0 which mean flake8 new version 3.9.0 can also
break the pep8 job if new check are added.

To avoid similar gate break in future, we need to bump the hacking min
version.

- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014828.html

Change-Id: Ie2b4f889d814431246b1049381ab57bcdf5284c1
'}]
commit_message:
Fix hacking min version to 3.0.1

flake8 new release 3.8.0 added new checks and gate pep8
job start failing. hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to
avoid bringing in a new version with new checks.

Though it is fixed in latest hacking but 2.0 and 3.0 has cap for
flake8 as <4.0.0 which mean flake8 new version 3.9.0 can also
break the pep8 job if new check are added.

To avoid similar gate break in future, we need to bump the hacking min
version.

- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014828.html

commit_message:
Fix hacking min version to 3.0.1

flake8 new release 3.8.0 added new checks and gate pep8
job start failing. hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to
avoid bringing in a new version with new checks.

Though it is fixed in latest hacking but 2.0 and 3.0 has cap for
flake8 as <4.0.0 which mean flake8 new version 3.9.0 can also
break the pep8 job if new check are added.

To avoid similar gate break in future, we need to bump the hacking min
version.

Also removing the hacking and other related dep from lower-constraints file
as theose are blacklisted requirements and does not need to be present
there.

- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014828.html

Change-Id: Icbbd8370dd24882b34e3616030ad4dedd1d565a0

commit_message:
Add test_ping_global_ip_from_vm_with_fip

We need such a test in order to be able to catch issues like [1].
The test creates network and server, then launches a VM with a FIP.
Then connects to the FIP and pings a global ip address.
The test requires global_ip_address variable in tempest.conf.
By default the value is not set and the test will be skipped.

[1] https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1834433

Change-Id: Ibb3db814ed9b42f28ced8378368a3d5c2e43d7b3

commit_message:
Bump hacking version to 3.0.0 and fix pep8 test

Some changes needed to increase hacking version, fixing it between
3.0.0 and 3.1.0, and add some options to tox.ini to be consistent
with other projects.

Also setting min version for pyflakes to 1.6.0 for Python 3.6
compatibility.

Change-Id: I564335a74698037c495b008e8c7102f0fa3b01c1

commit_message:
Fix ovn-db-sync-util after removing l3 ovsdb connection

As a result of d92e71c2 the sync util can fail because it tries to
look up the ovsdb connection from the mechanism_manager under 'ovn'
but the sync util registers under 'ovn-sync'.

Change-Id: I6998b08672761a501e427aab5d581064d9425dde
Closes-Bug: #1876752

commit_message:
Fix hacking min version to 3.0.1

flake8 new release 3.8.0 added new checks and gate pep8
job start failing. hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to
avoid bringing in a new version with new checks.

Though it is fixed in latest hacking but 2.0 and 3.0 has cap for
flake8 as <4.0.0 which mean flake8 new version 3.9.0 can also
break the pep8 job if new check are added.

To avoid similar gate break in future, we need to bump the hacking min
version.

- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014828.html

Change-Id: I117c0ff7fe10fa6a1fd1dee7c6de3ea1a1ee06f6

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-05-11 20:01:35.000000000', 'message': 'Add support for object replication handoffs_first

In extreme cases of object rebalance or node failure, swift environments
with millions of objects may have a hard time with objects landing in
handoff or misplaced partitions and the operator of the cloud may need
to prioritize migrating data in handoff partitions back to primary
partitions over the 3 primary partitions replicating amongst each other.

To allow for this, the object-server.conf [object-replicator]
configuration can have handoffs_first set to True which will force
the object-replicators to focus on handoff partitions before syncing
primary partitions for any given object partition.

Change-Id: I8b44c287567a0e6d634def0b13baf0fe4ad4aa7b
Closes-Bug: 1878087
'}]
commit_message:
Add support for object replication handoffs_first

In extreme cases of object rebalance or node failure, swift environments
with millions of objects may have a hard time with objects landing in
handoff or misplaced partitions and the operator of the cloud may need
to prioritize migrating data in handoff partitions back to primary
partitions over the 3 primary partitions replicating amongst each other.

To allow for this, the object-server.conf [object-replicator]
configuration can have handoffs_first set to True which will force
the object-replicators to focus on handoff partitions before syncing
primary partitions for any given object partition.

Change-Id: I8b44c287567a0e6d634def0b13baf0fe4ad4aa7b
Closes-Bug: 1878087

commit_message:
mech_driver.OVNMechanismDriver "_ovn_client" is a read-only property

mech_driver.OVNMechanismDriver "_ovn_client" is not a class member but
a read-only property and can't be assigned.

Backported from Neutron (Ussuri): https://review.opendev.org/#/c/715375

Closes-Bug: #1869342

Change-Id: I98f7deaeaad80c840cfccc0dfc3f6f97de05e088
(cherry picked from commit e32e750b35da16d1832fd081c30778031c5c4e4b)

commit_message:
Use centos proxy mirror for centos8 repos

Some of the repos shipped from delorean master repos have centos
mirror which got timeout due to network issue. Replacing those with
proxies mirror fixes the same.

Closes-Bug: #1879267

Change-Id: I59386bf504d2d3d370c30da75db34a1861bbb610
Signed-off-by: Chandan Kumar (raukadah) <chkumar@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Include vendordata in metadata api

The vendordata configuration is used not only in compute but also
in metadata, thus the module shuold be included in metadata class.

Change-Id: I5371e8ef3d04c26aba1518f7c212d62311b773f1

commit_message:
Revert "Run linters in a temp dir instead of an install"

Apparently galaxy is or will be running ansible-test sanity
on uploaded collections. This means we need to run on the
tarball, even though it loses symlinks - so we'll need to
put in ansible-test skips.

This reverts commit 6271268567fd6744141e2c7d3857b2982f694015.

Change-Id: I0c12d36ba9ca27eba0809b58a855e9d1a12ce2b5

commit_message:
Fix outdated comment in rootwrap filter

GlusterFS volume driver has been removed[1], and chgrp is now used
in NFS backup driver and GlusterFS backup driver.

[1] 16e93ccd4f3a6d62ed9d277f03b64bccc63ae060

Change-Id: I297274905a1416c6041c7572a89d9336e6951e60

commit_message:
Add link to PDF file

Create new config options to optionally link to a generate PDF file that
is published at the same location as the html files.

Note that the preview will not be able to download the file since
the file is in a different location. The publishing job moves the PDF
file in the top-level directory.

Change-Id: I3ff74030195b6a85ff4e4e3b62f367aa78f85b0a

commit_message:
Only restart rsyslog when it is installed

Task fails if the host/container does not have rsyslog present. We
can just skip the restart if it is not installed.

Change-Id: Ie4c9a42133c1f042c587cec48f53b4a87bd50952
(cherry picked from commit 38db41fbd61acbe2f50ad3391058649742b61a6c)

commit_message:
Do not refresh deleted instance info cache

When we try to refresh instance info cache on DELETED instances, it
fails with InstanceInfoCacheNotFound exception.
We cant refresh network info on DELETED instances.

Change-Id: I09eb70197138a2a12dde721a93cd7ef7f2fe1ae2
Signed-off-by: Arnaud Morin <arnaud.morin@corp.ovh.com>

commit_message:
Add shared volume for side-car wrapper locks

The lock used in the wrapper is under /var/lock in the container which
is not shared with the host so the sync script never waits for the
wrapper to be done. Moving the lock file to a path on a shared mount in
the container seems to solve that particular race.

Partial-bug: #1874470

Change-Id: Iaa3a19bc47241e6eb686d65c1a198ec69505398e
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobreli@redhat.com>

[{'created': '2020-05-14 09:01:11.000000000', 'message': '[OVN]: Make _delete_port() more error-resilent

This patch is making the transaction from the _delete_port() method in
OVNClient more resilient to errors where elements from that transaction
have already been deleted by another change in the database.

Prior to this patch, a few places could potentially raise RowNotFound
which would abort the whole transaction and would leave the a stable
port for being cleaned up after by the maintenance thread. This patch
tries to catch those exceptions that could potentially fail the
transaction.

Change-Id: I8fd1d1485269d23529a19085bd4aa4c6c74f5f91
Partial-Bug: #1874733
Signed-off-by: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 8b234d8786072c9bc83d19e0cde3927fc5ccf8f8)
'}]
commit_message:
[OVN]: Make _delete_port() more error-resilent

This patch is making the transaction from the _delete_port() method in
OVNClient more resilient to errors where elements from that transaction
have already been deleted by another change in the database.

Prior to this patch, a few places could potentially raise RowNotFound
which would abort the whole transaction and would leave the a stable
port for being cleaned up after by the maintenance thread. This patch
tries to catch those exceptions that could potentially fail the
transaction.

Change-Id: I8fd1d1485269d23529a19085bd4aa4c6c74f5f91
Partial-Bug: #1874733
Signed-off-by: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>
(cherry picked from commit 8b234d8786072c9bc83d19e0cde3927fc5ccf8f8)

[{'created': '2020-05-11 19:47:30.000000000', 'message': 'Fix compliance tests

Change I65c50722f5990f540d84fa361b997302bbc935c5 moved our base test
code from cinder.test to cinder.tests.unit.test. It included updates for
all unit tests, but missed the compliance tests that are also based on
it.

This fixes the imports for the compliance tests to use the new location
to import the module.

Change-Id: I510f7707085b917ed45e674eeffb67c9ca444088
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Fix compliance tests

Change I65c50722f5990f540d84fa361b997302bbc935c5 moved our base test
code from cinder.test to cinder.tests.unit.test. It included updates for
all unit tests, but missed the compliance tests that are also based on
it.

This fixes the imports for the compliance tests to use the new location
to import the module.

Change-Id: I510f7707085b917ed45e674eeffb67c9ca444088
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Document and test maximum supported version of Ansible

The Train release supports up to Ansible 2.9. This patch states this in
the documentation, and updates our testing to match.

Change-Id: I83d068a242d2e64b5e971be1549935f87641cf8e
Closes-Bug: #1878328

commit_message:
multipath requires udev-rules in host

install sg3-utils-udev if multipath is enabled, else SCSI_IDENT*
vars are missing in udev.

Closes-Bug: 1877509
Change-Id: Ib205f3cdb775c9cfa719325f702f4fad196d346b
(cherry picked from commit 5dfc270a62dae3c653a08231eca1cd790cdec60e)

commit_message:
Use consistent logging

Sphinx itself prefixes everything it logs with '[app]'. Historically we
had done this with '[openstackdocstheme]', but we seem to have lost our
way recently. In addition, Sphinx automatically logs everything at info
level, which means we were generating a lot of noise.

Resolve both issues by modifying our logs, adding the
'[openstackdocstheme]' prefix in the places it's missing from and lower
the logging level for those that don't need to be shown every time from
info to debug.

Change-Id: Ic116367ea7c6fc6d78b70e9c115898bae6ec6d96
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <sfinucan@redhat.com>

Also that there is perhaps a workaround to disabled that via ksmtune.conf"}, {'account_id': 15140, 'date': '2018-08-16 18:05:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Melanie, Sahid,

I would like to indicate that the flag set by this "new extra spec" is already implemented and can be triggered by "hw:realtime" spec, but that adds additional flags which may not be wanted for a given situation. The goal of this new extra spec is to allow triggering only this function, without others. We can rename it to "no_share_pages" to make it match the internal code and libvirt setting better. Otherwise it's just a stripped down portion of "hw:realtime" flag. Please let me know if this is reasonable and trivial enough to keep it without a spec.'}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2018-08-16 18:47:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

> Melanie, Sahid,
 > 
 > I would like to indicate that the flag set by this "new extra spec"
 > is already implemented and can be triggered by "hw:realtime" spec,
 > but that adds additional flags which may not be wanted for a given
 > situation. The goal of this new extra spec is to allow triggering
 > only this function, without others. We can rename it to
 > "no_share_pages" to make it match the internal code and libvirt
 > setting better. Otherwise it's just a stripped down portion of
 > "hw:realtime" flag. Please let me know if this is reasonable and
 > trivial enough to keep it without a spec.

I see what you mean, but one of the main points reviewers want to discuss is around disabling KSM being per instance rather than per host. The "hw:realtime" extra spec was added as part of a nova spec [1] for adding support for real time instances where the per-instance aspect was discussed and agreed to be appropriate. Reviewers have questions about whether disabling KSM per instance is appropriate and that discussion, along with other questions about the use case for this, would be best contained on a spec review proposal.

[1] https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/nova-specs/specs/mitaka/implemented/libvirt-real-time.html'}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2018-08-17 07:36:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Drimity, for realtime the instance's vCPUs are pinned to a set of pCPUs, those pCPUs should be isolated so we can expect that any work on host should not affect the instance that is using "realtime".

Based on your proposal, you don't indicate that this option is for example only available with a cpu_policy:dedicated... That is a option possible so using extra-spec could make sense but if we consider that without pinning I guess a per host option will be more appropriated.

Melanie is right, we should probably discuss all of that in a spec, I don't think that will be something big.

Is that reasonable for you?'}, {'account_id': 15140, 'date': '2018-08-17 21:25:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I've created a spec - https://review.openstack.org/593197"}, {'account_id': 15334, 'date': '2020-05-18 13:06:32.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

It looks like work on both this and the spec have stalled, so I'm going to abandon this for now. We can restore it if people are interested in working on this still."}]

commit_message:
libvirt: add disabling KSM via flavor extra specs

KSM stands for Kernel same-page merging, relevant to linux and qemu.
It is usually enabled by default in qemu, but may cause issues with specific
workloads (for example freezing), so tenant admin should have an option
to disable it.

Change-Id: I4fd46c266910db08e9f71d52505d12f7f044bc61
Implements: blueprint allow-disabling-ksm-via-extra-specs

commit_message:
Cleanup bindep

The repo is now python3 only, remove python2 devel package
(python-dev).

Remove tags for precise, it's not supported.

All current RPM distros have python3-devel, so use it.

Change-Id: Ibf4a712d90d7a2a9483e42952174d20630af2fb6

commit_message:
Enable parallel building

This theme provides a sphinx extension that is used with parallel
building, thus enable parallel building so that we can sure it works
everywhere.

The time benefit is not worth the work, this is for testing.

Change-Id: I4e8b7fdb5c4b8c6bd738211802567b532528ab9a

commit_message:
Fix pep8

This patch fixes the issues that pep8  is showing in our CI.
Flake8 changes in tox.ini:
-Added ironic/tests/base.py and  ironic/cmd/__init__.py
to per-file-ignores to ignore E402.
-Added E741 to ignore.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Change-Id: Icf92aa186fb4b2be0d59736a56260d01a5c3279a

commit_message:
Move all infrared_plugin/main.yml set_facts to vars

Currently all these variables are set via set_fact. Each set_fact
takes time. We can set all these variables to the same values and
have them all load with the playbook by moving them to playbook
vars.

This is far quicker.

Change-Id: I60c70ac90006f52f44b018e94f10fae48e464bd1

commit_message:
Use tempest version 23.0.0 for stable/train python2 job

The tempest and neutron-tempest-plugin projects no longer supports python
2 on its master branch [0][1]

https://docs.openstack.org/releasenotes/neutron-tempest-plugin/unreleased.html#relnotes-1-0-0

Signed-off-by: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Don't run tripleo-ci-centos-7-undercloud-upgrades in queens

ceph-ansible requires ansible >= 2.4.2.0 which is not available
in CentOS Extras anymore. As pike is EOL we can possibly remove
this upgrade job from queens to fix CI.

Change-Id: Iaa5b02691b450a50b249fc32cd7ecafc3aaf1870
Closes-Bug: #1877031

commit_message:
Encapsulate auth_token middleware

The existing public routes middleware wrapper subclasses the
keystoneauth middleware. This change refactors it to an encapsulation
of any middleware. In the future this allows for different auth
strategies by passing different auth middleware.

Change-Id: I51ae072e596e987334b79a0b6dfc4905bcf2bcef
Story: 2007656
Task: 39769

commit_message:
CI: Add overcloud host configure jobs

Backport note: added CentOS 7 job

Tests various non-default configuration:

* Custom users
* Network interfaces, VLANs, bridges, bonds
* Software RAID
* LVM & docker devicemapper
* timezone
* Package mirrors
* yum-cron / DNF automatic

This improved test coverage allows us to be more confident about these
features working on CentOS 8.

Story: 2006574

commit_message:
Allow OVS bridges to connect directly to interface

Currently we require a Linux bridge to exist between OVS and the
physical interface. This is necessary if you want to set an IP on the
native VLAN of that interface, but that is not always the case.

This change allows the physical interface (or any non-bridge interface)
to be plugged into OVS.

Change-Id: I2172a74f4719605f6ec81fadec46ce49f8310a96
Story: 2007364
Task: 38920

[{'created': '2020-04-29 18:25:40.000000000', 'message': 'Fix ironic inspector rule creation idempotency

Ironic inspector rules are registered both with the seed and (if using)
overcloud ironic inspector services. These tasks often show up as
changed even when no configuration changes have been made that would
affect the rules.

This is caused by inspector returning default values for fields that may
be omitted in the requested rule. This change fixes the issue by
including those defaults in the comparison.

commit_message:
Fix ironic inspector rule creation idempotency

Ironic inspector rules are registered both with the seed and (if using)
overcloud ironic inspector services. These tasks often show up as
changed even when no configuration changes have been made that would
affect the rules.

This is caused by inspector returning default values for fields that may
be omitted in the requested rule. This change fixes the issue by
including those defaults in the comparison.

Change-Id: Ia24e328d4531201d76a65b6385e4463bb1f3c5c6
Story: 2007399
Task: 38997
(cherry picked from commit 2a00b4cc67df91c5eac10f4762aff543d3740e05)

commit_message:
Upgrade Monasca Fluentd output plugin

As part of the support for using the unified Monasca API for logs, the
Fluentd Monasca output plugin has been upgraded. Any custom Fluentd
configuration which forwards logs to Monasca will need to be updated.

Change-Id: I7deefec590cd3bfc774b47867d968afe1bd69d99

commit_message:
[k8s] Support configurable health polling interval

The default 10 seconds health polling interval is too frequent for most of
the cases. Now it has been changed to 60s. A new config
`health_polling_interval` is added to make the interval configurable.
Cloud admin can totally disable the health polling by set a negative value
for the config.

Task: 39795
Story: 2007683

Change-Id: Iad30487b8c119e94ee21d75f53fb86eb23dff365
(cherry picked from commit 8e9df14d2773a16c21d2c7c52e3e9d40dd0f84df)

commit_message:
CI: Add ansible-lint to tox

* Reworked tox pep8 into linters job, that runs:
  - pep8
  - bandit
  - bashate
  - doc8
  - yamllint
  - ansible-lint (validate-all-files.py + ansible-lint)

* Skip E701 - missing galaxy_info in meta and E602 see [1].
* Skip E301 and E503 - followup later in a separate change
* Added ansible-role-jobs to zuul.d/project.yaml which will run
  openstack-tox-linters job in check queue
* Fixed remaining style issue
* Made tox and docs reference the new env for linters
* Dropped pype environment (not supported)

[1]: https://github.com/ansible/ansible-lint/issues/457

Change-Id: I494b4b151804aac8173120e6c6e42bc2fdb00234

commit_message:
switch to official CentOS 8 repositories

RDO builds of stable/train for CentOS 8 went into phase when we do not
need to use delorean builds.

EPEL is disabled like it is in Ussuri (RDO packages may conflict with
it).

Erlang for RabbitMQ is used from CentOS 8 'rabbitmq-38' repo while
RabbitMQ is still 3.7.* from same place as usual.

'python3-pika' is dropped from openstack-base as it is EPEL only package
and is not used by any image (dropped in Ussuri in
https://review.opendev.org/#/c/710003/ patch)

AArch64 is not supported until CentOS 8.2 release.

Change-Id: I9d3ed54f4d10ef7ad2d52ed3aeca15f3968cd163

commit_message:
Optimize QoS bound objects queries

Optimize the following methods:
- get_bound_networks
- get_bound_ports
- get_bound_floatingips
- get_bound_routers

Those methods, using the "QosPolicy_XXXX_Binding" OVO interface, were
retrieving all objects with a certain policy ID and then returning
only the ID of the _XXXX_ object. That means to retrieve a full
register list from the DB, then converted them to OVOs and extract
only the _XXXX_ ID.

This patch retrieves only the _XXXX_ object IDs from the DB and
returns the list, without the OVO conversion.

Change-Id: I891eba93b3b4abaec8ada13a032b5440cbb0548d
Closes-Bug: #1877560

commit_message:
Update TOX/UPPER_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/train

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/train branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I16589c8ac7fd8c8d2ad5edb1ec6e7244478a2f32

commit_message:
Bump hacking min version to 3.0.1

hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to avoid bringing in a new
version with new checks.

bumping the min version for hacking so that any older hacking versions
which auto adopt the new checks are not used.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/728335/

Change-Id: Ie00c10332bd7110169dbb150d601c157b6694d05

commit_message:
[ovn] devstack needs to support openflow15

OVN has been changed to use Openflow15 [1].

Instead of creating br-int and setting the openflow version
via ovn_agent script, it is better to delegate the bridge
creation to the ovn-controller. Thus, having ovn-controller
creating br-int addresses the potential version mismatch.

[1]: https://github.com/ovn-org/ovn/commit/6ec0b82038052866533f12823fe410308b3e457a

Change-Id: I62e4e98556c71312a7cf85b6246ddbecbc59a039
Related-Bug: #1871239
Closes-Bug: #1877195
(cherry picked from commit ba16d2fc742bbb9c80f1aec2cbb6de8033d051e5)

commit_message:
[k8s] Support configurable health polling interval

The default 10 seconds health polling interval is too frequent for most of
the cases. Now it has been changed to 60s. A new config
`health_polling_interval` is added to make the interval configurable.
Cloud admin can totally disable the health polling by set a negative value
for the config.

Task: 39795
Story: 2007683

Change-Id: Iad30487b8c119e94ee21d75f53fb86eb23dff365
(cherry picked from commit 8e9df14d2773a16c21d2c7c52e3e9d40dd0f84df)

[{'created': '2020-05-11 11:46:56.000000000', 'message': "Add support for OVN LB selection fields

Prior this patch OVN Octavia provider driver used
default 5-tuple-hash algorithm which is pretty similar to
SOURCE_IP_PORT.

Unfornutelly because of the bug described here [1] it
was not clear how 5-tuple-hash works and some inconsistencies
between kernel and user space implementations were found.

OVN recently added support for selective fields in OVN LB, to
explicitly define what fields are being hashed to tackle this problem.

This commit adds support for that kind of hashing. If installation
of OVN on which OVN Octavia provider is running doesn't support
selective fields - it will use old behavior.

[1] https://mail.openvswitch.org/pipermail/ovs-discuss/2020-April/049896.html
[2] https://github.com/ovn-org/ovn/commit/5af304e7478adcf5ac50ed41e96a55bebebff3e8

commit_message:
Add support for OVN LB selection fields

Prior this patch OVN Octavia provider driver used
default 5-tuple-hash algorithm which is pretty similar to
SOURCE_IP_PORT.

Unfornutelly because of the bug described here [1] it
was not clear how 5-tuple-hash works and some inconsistencies
between kernel and user space implementations were found.

OVN recently added support for selective fields in OVN LB, to
explicitly define what fields are being hashed to tackle this problem.

This commit adds support for that kind of hashing. If installation
of OVN on which OVN Octavia provider is running doesn't support
selective fields - it will use old behavior.

[1] https://mail.openvswitch.org/pipermail/ovs-discuss/2020-April/049896.html
[2] https://github.com/ovn-org/ovn/commit/5af304e7478adcf5ac50ed41e96a55bebebff3e8


Change-Id: I7b4ab99d1be2855e18b186557990c85f170ad548
Closes-Bug: #1871239

commit_message:
Trigger udev rescan if pv_dev disappears

Workaround for kernel by in Ubuntu 20.04 LTS.

When using by-dname device paths with MAAS and bcache, the pvcreate
operation results in the by-dname entry for the block device being
deleted.  The subsequent vgcreate then fails as the path cannot
be found.

Trigger a rescan of block devices if the pv_dev path does not
exists after the pvcreate operation.

Change-Id: If7e11f6bd1effd2d5fc2dc5abbaba6865104006f
Depends-On: Ifb16c47ae5ff316cbcfc3798de3446a3774fa012
Related-Bug: 1878752

commit_message:
Update the minversion parameter.

Update the minversion parameter to use the python -m pip to install
python packages:

https://tox.readthedocs.io/en/latest/changelog.html#id185

It's recommend to use this. Remove the useless install_command
parameter.

Change-Id: I8c6081d58e22db10c62e2706a8fcddfccb3fa69d

commit_message:
Trigger udev rescan if pv_dev disappears

Workaround for kernel by in Ubuntu 20.04 LTS.

When using by-dname device paths with MAAS and bcache, the pvcreate
operation results in the by-dname entry for the block device being
deleted.  The subsequent vgcreate then fails as the path cannot
be found.

Trigger a rescan of block devices if the pv_dev path does not
exists after the pvcreate operation.

Change-Id: Ifb16c47ae5ff316cbcfc3798de3446a3774fa012
Related-Bug: 1878752

commit_message:
Trigger udev rescan if pv_dev disappears

Workaround for kernel by in Ubuntu 20.04 LTS.

When using by-dname device paths with MAAS and bcache, the pvcreate
operation results in the by-dname entry for the block device being
deleted.  The subsequent vgcreate then fails as the path cannot
be found.

Trigger a rescan of block devices if the pv_dev path does not
exists after the pvcreate operation.

Change-Id: Ifb16c47ae5ff316cbcfc3798de3446a3774fa012
Related-Bug: 1878752
(cherry picked from commit 2d61a56544e8932795694c16cd8cb18282c2ffe6)

commit_message:
Cleanup deprecated iteritems of dict

To fix the issue because of using deprecated method in python3, replace
iteritems() with items(). Although tacker itself does not cause the
error because it uses `six` actually, no need to keep python2 support.

Change-Id: Ifec7d5d3146ffe01addcb1e5c0ab78ce92bae0ff
Related-Bug: 1872120

commit_message:
Add UT instead of deleting FT related with Mistral

This patch deletes the FT related with Mistral for the following reasons.
- Other OpenStack-PJs (e.g. nova and heat) that have Action definition in
mistral([1]) do not implement FT in each PJ.
- These functional tests are carried out in the mistral-tempest-plugin.
However, at the moment, only core PJs (e.g. nova and heat) are targeted in [2],
and it's necessary to aim to add tacker here in the future.

In this patch, instead of deleting FT, the viewpoint of unittest is added to
confirm that mistral-client is called as expected.
The code is modified so that the anchor notation is not used
because not supported by mistral in [3].

[1]: https://opendev.org/openstack/mistral-extra/src/branch/master/mistral_extra/actions/openstack/mapping.json
[2]: https://opendev.org/openstack/mistral-tempest-plugin/src/branch/master/mistral_tempest_tests/tests/scenario/engine/actions/v2/test_openstack_actions.py
[3]: https://opendev.org/openstack/mistral/commit/eac23d9e774f658f9d4743c99aa2743eb104c3f9

Closes-Bug: #1878309
Change-Id: Ie8eab1b262c15f7b53796a287b333e60ffee1c31

commit_message:
Labels override

This adds a boolean flag called --merge-labels at the create CLIs
for clusters and nodegroups. The show output for clusters and
nodegroups is modified to contain also new fields called
"labels_overridden", "labels_added", "labels_skipped". The new labels
contain the differences of the object's labels with its parent's.

commit_message:
Add timeout and retries to JSON RPC client

The necessary options are already in keystoneauth, but have empty
defaults. This patch changes timeout to 15 and adds 2 retries by default.

Change-Id: Idf8cfa54b77be6f5127d2c9d587a427aa0898802
(cherry picked from commit 14524c265b4104bf9cf4eeeae21fbb1eca2cecbc)

commit_message:
[k8s-fedora-atomic] Build kube_tag v1.15.12

Despite the policy that Kubernetes project maintains release branches
for the most recent three minor releases (1.18, 1.17, 1.16) [0],
v1.15.12 has been released so this change partially restores the
builder for this tag as an alternative to completely reverting
26411c2970df4c939c63ff173ea66e53eba5aede.

[0] https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/release/version-skew-policy/#supported-versions

Story: 2005124
Task: 39686

Change-Id: Ia458c5a87ba2357f845eb095548403cc7a25b58c

commit_message:
[k8s] Support configurable health polling interval

The default 10 seconds health polling interval is too frequent for most of
the cases. Now it has been changed to 60s. A new config
`health_polling_interval` is added to make the interval configurable.
Cloud admin can totally disable the health polling by set a negative value
for the config.

Task: 39795
Story: 2007683

Change-Id: Iad30487b8c119e94ee21d75f53fb86eb23dff365

[{'created': '2020-05-15 13:49:09.000000000', 'message': 'Fix Field `health_status_reason[api]' cannot be None`

If nodes in a cluster were deleted, period health checks for the cluster
will timeout. This will result in logs of logs like the following:

 ERROR oslo.service.loopingcall ValueError: Field
 `health_status_reason[api]' cannot be None

The timeout is successfully caught by exception handling in this part of
the code. However, it is thrown as a type MaxRetryError exception, which
does not have body or message attrs. E.g.

 MaxRetryError("HTTPSConnectionPool(host='115.146.81.72', port=6443): Max
 retries exceeded with url: /healthz (Caused by
 NewConnectionError('<urllib3.connection.VerifiedHTTPSConnection object
 at 0x7f6b9b915a20>: Failed to establish a new connection: [Errno 110]
 ETIMEDOUT',))",)

This means health_status_reason will be a dict like `{'api': None}`.
Saving this using oslo_versionedobjects will throw an ValueError,
because althought the dict itself is corced as a `Dict(default=<class
'oslo_versionedobjects.fields.UnspecifiedDefault'>,nullable=True)`, the
None value will be coerced as a `String(default=<class
'oslo_versionedobjects.fields.UnspecifiedDefault'>,nullable=False)` and
that is not nullable.

Task: 38316
Change-Id: I8fd8d363284b06cf0bfba45d5845ba8687a2c783
(cherry picked from commit 30436350afb88dc3e62af872aa2b39cf439e8eae)
(cherry picked from commit 62c5de074391c3922504f0e185ec0c9d4af633bd)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix Field `health_status_reason[api]' cannot be None`

If nodes in a cluster were deleted, period health checks for the cluster
will timeout. This will result in logs of logs like the following:

 ERROR oslo.service.loopingcall ValueError: Field
 `health_status_reason[api]' cannot be None

The timeout is successfully caught by exception handling in this part of
the code. However, it is thrown as a type MaxRetryError exception, which
does not have body or message attrs. E.g.

 MaxRetryError("HTTPSConnectionPool(host='115.146.81.72', port=6443): Max
 retries exceeded with url: /healthz (Caused by
 NewConnectionError('<urllib3.connection.VerifiedHTTPSConnection object
 at 0x7f6b9b915a20>: Failed to establish a new connection: [Errno 110]
 ETIMEDOUT',))",)

This means health_status_reason will be a dict like `{'api': None}`.
Saving this using oslo_versionedobjects will throw an ValueError,
because althought the dict itself is corced as a `Dict(default=<class
'oslo_versionedobjects.fields.UnspecifiedDefault'>,nullable=True)`, the
None value will be coerced as a `String(default=<class
'oslo_versionedobjects.fields.UnspecifiedDefault'>,nullable=False)` and
that is not nullable.

Task: 38316
Change-Id: I8fd8d363284b06cf0bfba45d5845ba8687a2c783
(cherry picked from commit 30436350afb88dc3e62af872aa2b39cf439e8eae)
(cherry picked from commit 62c5de074391c3922504f0e185ec0c9d4af633bd)

commit_message:
Ensure neutron-common installed before release assessment

Ensure that the neutron-common package is installed prior to
assessment of any feature requirements based on OpenStack release.

This ensures that the OpenStack release is assessed accurately
avoiding any issues with guesswork and assumption in the charm
code.

Change-Id: I86a73fe363c91627f59b1c181d9c2f75f7b06e0b
Closes-Bug: 1878750

commit_message:
Cap pycodestyle to be < 2.6.0

The 2.6.0 version introduces some checks that cause failures
with the current code. To avoid that, cap pycodestyle to a
version that had been tested without errors.

Had to remove cap on neutron in requirements.txt, but it
still used version 14.x.x in tests.

commit_message:
Trigger udev rescan if pv_dev disappears

Workaround for kernel by in Ubuntu 20.04 LTS.

When using by-dname device paths with MAAS and bcache, the pvcreate
operation results in the by-dname entry for the block device being
deleted.  The subsequent vgcreate then fails as the path cannot
be found.

Trigger a rescan of block devices if the pv_dev path does not
exists after the pvcreate operation.

Change-Id: If7e11f6bd1effd2d5fc2dc5abbaba6865104006f
Related-Bug: 1878752
(cherry picked from commit a45bc9ae8625be5dacbd308c1b11ce808b0ad1dd)

commit_message:
WIP: Read helm-config from files

The helm can now be configured by using three different arguments:
* helm_chart [1]
* helm_requirements [2]
* helm_values [3]

This parameters point to a .yaml file on which the user can
define what helms install on the cluster by means of {1,2,3}.
This also allows for the user to customize the magnum defined
applications by submitting only [3] overwritting default values
with custom ones.

Task: 36698
Story: 2004215

Change-Id: Ie53ac0452d15aa81d1bd368cf718e21d26e27576
Signed-off-by: Diogo Guerra <diogo.filipe.tomas.guerra@cern.ch>

global variable. This solution is based on that documented at:

commit_message:
CI: Discern between Ironic client and grep failure

Pipe hid an issue that Ironic client was not available in CI,
making it look as if fake-hardware driver was not usable.

This commit applies separation of concerns to easily discern
between the two failures and provide better debugging experience.

Change-Id: Iac3d84b7d707b84a8426c8d787b29a368ff7ae85
Related-Bug: #1872481

commit_message:
container_manage: catch more containers with wrong return code

- helpers/haskey: add excluded_keys argument. It allows to return the
  config that has an attribute but also where some attributed are
  excluded. The use case here is that we have some container configs
  which have both "command" and "action". We want to use that filter to
  build a list of containers where the return code has to be checked;
  which is the not the case for the containers with "action" in their
  configs; since they are used for "podman exec" configs (and there is
  nothing to check in return from podman inspect).

- check_exit_code: change the list of containers to check the exit code
  to include all the containers with a "command" but not "action".
  It should cover all the containers which are used to run some
  non-services things like db_sync etc.

- molecule: change the fedora_bis and fedora_three containers to run
  short sleep so we can actually test that change against these
  containers and also on the first deployment of fedora_bis and
  fedora_three, we'll check their return code.

Change-Id: I466a57bd788e02c32b1efb0ac0223684f0d39393
Closes-Bug: #1878074
(cherry picked from commit 504033868672580b3af2b9d1e5d771a8233add9d)

commit_message:
buildah: exclude build and push, not only build

When adding exclude param, we put it in the build but buildah still
tries to pushes the images from exclude. Let's just move it to the
_generate_container method which takes care of both build & push.

Change-Id: I53108786e384215353b5db37b3d5a6d77e0c9d60
(cherry picked from commit 78bcbfff5094f10d05c8cc4964b4f07c1bcc9efd)

commit_message:
Move all infrared_plugin/main.yml set_facts to vars

Currently all these variables are set via set_fact. Each set_fact
takes time. We can set all these variables to the same values and
have them all load with the playbook by moving them to playbook
vars.

This is far quicker.

Change-Id: I60c70ac90006f52f44b018e94f10fae48e464bd1
(cherry picked from commit 427e8c49bfa74df7bf59fa8568dde9f41f9ab7e4)

[{'created': '2020-05-12 18:53:45.000000000', 'message': 'Stop explicitly requiring pycodestyle

pip doesn't have a dependency resolver. Instead, it "simply uses the
first specification it finds for a project." [1] In Train, keystone
switched from hacking 0.12.x/0.13.x to hacking 1.1.x [2]. That change
explicitly added a pycodestyle dependency for reasons that aren't
entirely clear to me, but pip's broken dependency resolution leads to
the below funkiness when trying to install the dependencies.

  ERROR: flake8 2.6.2 has requirement pycodestyle<2.1,>=2.0, but you'll have pycodestyle 2.5.0 which is incompatible.

As seen below, this can be easily reproduced and seems to happen because
pip doesn't go further than one level of dependencies, meaning it knows
about the dependency on flake8<2.7.0,>=2.6.0 from hacking, but not the
dependency on pycodestyle<2.1,>=2.0 that this in-turn introduces.

  $ virtualenv venv
  $ source venv/bin/activate
  $ (venv) cat requirements.txt
  hacking>=1.1.0,<1.2.0 # Apache-2.0
  pycodestyle>=2.0.0 # MIT License

  $ pip install -r requirements-new.txt
  Collecting hacking<1.2.0,>=1.1.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting pycodestyle>=2.0.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting six>=1.10.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting flake8<2.7.0,>=2.6.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting pbr!=2.1.0,>=2.0.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting mccabe<0.6,>=0.2.1
    Using cached ...
  Collecting pyflakes!=1.2.0,!=1.2.1,!=1.2.2,<1.3,>=0.8.1
    Using cached ...
  ERROR: flake8 2.6.2 has requirement pycodestyle<2.1,>=2.0, but you'll have pycodestyle 2.5.0 which is incompatible.
  Installing collected packages: six, pycodestyle, mccabe, pyflakes, flake8, pbr, hacking
  Successfully installed flake8-2.6.2 hacking-1.1.0 mccabe-0.5.3 pbr-5.4.3 pycodestyle-2.5.0 pyflakes-1.2.3 six-1.12.0

The solution is simple: stop explicitly requiring this dependency and
instead rely on flake8 bringing it in.

[1] https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/user_guide/#requirements-files
[2] I3fc591e09c1e25a3bd2a3922880772ea9617f1e3

Change-Id: Ic0991d3eeae018609be0ecbd43fa0b0b9f13d6ba
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <sfinucan@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 5c71ebd7a92d25df83e2e7cc5fad9990e9eebbf5)

the below funkiness when trying to install the dependencies.

  ERROR: flake8 2.6.2 has requirement pycodestyle<2.1,>=2.0, but you'll have pycodestyle 2.5.0 which is incompatible.

As seen below, this can be easily reproduced and seems to happen because
pip doesn't go further than one level of dependencies, meaning it knows
about the dependency on flake8<2.7.0,>=2.6.0 from hacking, but not the
dependency on pycodestyle<2.1,>=2.0 that this in-turn introduces.

  $ virtualenv venv
  $ source venv/bin/activate

  hacking>=1.1.0,<1.2.0 # Apache-2.0
  pycodestyle>=2.0.0 # MIT License

commit_message:
Stop explicitly requiring pycodestyle

pip doesn't have a dependency resolver. Instead, it "simply uses the
first specification it finds for a project." [1] In Train, keystone
switched from hacking 0.12.x/0.13.x to hacking 1.1.x [2]. That change
explicitly added a pycodestyle dependency for reasons that aren't
entirely clear to me, but pip's broken dependency resolution leads to
the below funkiness when trying to install the dependencies.

  ERROR: flake8 2.6.2 has requirement pycodestyle<2.1,>=2.0, but you'll have pycodestyle 2.5.0 which is incompatible.

As seen below, this can be easily reproduced and seems to happen because
pip doesn't go further than one level of dependencies, meaning it knows
about the dependency on flake8<2.7.0,>=2.6.0 from hacking, but not the
dependency on pycodestyle<2.1,>=2.0 that this in-turn introduces.

  $ virtualenv venv
  $ source venv/bin/activate
  $ (venv) cat requirements.txt
  hacking>=1.1.0,<1.2.0 # Apache-2.0
  pycodestyle>=2.0.0 # MIT License

  $ pip install -r requirements-new.txt
  Collecting hacking<1.2.0,>=1.1.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting pycodestyle>=2.0.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting six>=1.10.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting flake8<2.7.0,>=2.6.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting pbr!=2.1.0,>=2.0.0
    Using cached ...
  Collecting mccabe<0.6,>=0.2.1
    Using cached ...
  Collecting pyflakes!=1.2.0,!=1.2.1,!=1.2.2,<1.3,>=0.8.1
    Using cached ...
  ERROR: flake8 2.6.2 has requirement pycodestyle<2.1,>=2.0, but you'll have pycodestyle 2.5.0 which is incompatible.
  Installing collected packages: six, pycodestyle, mccabe, pyflakes, flake8, pbr, hacking
  Successfully installed flake8-2.6.2 hacking-1.1.0 mccabe-0.5.3 pbr-5.4.3 pycodestyle-2.5.0 pyflakes-1.2.3 six-1.12.0

The solution is simple: stop explicitly requiring this dependency and
instead rely on flake8 bringing it in.

[1] https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/user_guide/#requirements-files
[2] I3fc591e09c1e25a3bd2a3922880772ea9617f1e3

This cherry-pick includes an update to setup.cfg to align the
python-memcached version with global requirements.

Change-Id: Ic0991d3eeae018609be0ecbd43fa0b0b9f13d6ba
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <sfinucan@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 5c71ebd7a92d25df83e2e7cc5fad9990e9eebbf5)

Add py38 package metadata

commit_message:
Use effective MAC address for macvtap assigned VFs

This commit modifies the way sriov agent retrieves mac
addresses for macvtap assigned VFs to use the effective
mac taken from the macvtap net device instead of the
administrative mac set on the PF.

This commit rids sriov agent from depending on hypervisor/nova
to set both administrative and effective mac for macvtap ports.

Related-Bug: #1841067

Change-Id: Id499bcc49d27f13f7f03481922a3383b4a255da1
(cherry picked from commit 6f7b88d0808bee36b9d089ce8d3c0f98ae0b2dea)

commit_message:
Add focal-ussuri and bionic-ussuri bundle

This patch adds a focal-ussuri and bionic-ussuri bundles to the tests
for the charm.

Also removes 'admin-token' from the tests, as the keystone charm no
longer accepts the option.

Also, for focal, btrfs-tools has been removed and replaced by
btrfs-progs; thus these are installed on focal instead.  See linked Bug.

Closes-Bug: #1871712
Change-Id: Ifc79beebb981571cebc38be6cb6c2748d22816c9

commit_message:
Rebuild for sync charm-helpers for 20.05 release

Due to the ha change in charm-manila [0] xenial-mitaka and xenial-ocata
are no longer supported by manila.  Hence remove them from the gate.

[0]: I1f501283db3db1338d47a89a7688cf5035d08a7a

Change-Id: Ifcd489d1c58abba7776dcd1c2b56777e552539a2

commit_message:
Add service name filter to service list api-ref

Filter services by name is possible[1] but not documented in the
Keystone api-ref[2]. This commit add the filter in the doc.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/keystone/api/services.py#L37
[2] https://docs.openstack.org/api-ref/identity/v3/?expanded=list-services-detail#list-services

Change-Id: I91dea69a4c30fe37a23f3697cb8511fed0bfcec7
Closes-Bug: #1877851

commit_message:
tox: Keeping going with docs

1. Sphinx 1.8 introduced [1] the '--keep-going' argument which, as its name
suggests, keeps the build running when it encounters non-fatal errors.
This is exceptionally useful in avoiding a continuous edit-build loop
when undertaking large doc reworks where multiple errors may be
introduced.
2. Remove the exists folder before run sphinx-build command

[1] https://github.com/sphinx-doc/sphinx/commit/e3483e9b045

Change-Id: I1b1b45bf3ae104defbb16282e18995a28f67f649

commit_message:
Only restart rsyslog when it is installed

Task fails if the host/container does not have rsyslog present. We
can just skip the restart if it is not installed.

Change-Id: Ie4c9a42133c1f042c587cec48f53b4a87bd50952

commit_message:
kolla-toolbox: use only binary packages

We use virtualenv for all Python stuff. But all those packages can be
taken from distribution so we do not need to install compilers and
headers.

Resulting image is over 300 megabytes smaller.

Change-Id: I564fa390004a749f5ce2ba524dda271cbf1145b7

commit_message:
gnocchi: do not install cradox - use rados

https://github.com/sileht/pycradox website says:

"!DON'T USE IT, but use upstream python-rados, except you really can't!"

And this was 'pip' installed in binary images which is not how it should
happen.

Change-Id: I46c80df36ed435a3fb505066783fd0128609d31c

commit_message:
Configure RabbitMQ user tags in nova-cell role

The RabbitMQ 'openstack' user has the 'administrator' tag assigned via
the RabbitMQ definitions.json file.

Since the Train release, the nova-cell role also configures the RabbitMQ
user, but omits the tag. This causes the tag to be removed from the
user, which prevents it from accessing the management UI and API.

This change adds support for configuring user tags to the
service-rabbitmq role, and sets the administrator tag by default.

Change-Id: I7a5d6fe324dd133e0929804d431583e5b5c1853d
Closes-Bug: #1875786

commit_message:
Separate per-service host configuration tasks

Currently there are a few services that perform host configuration
tasks. This is done in config.yml. This means that these changes are
performed during 'kolla-ansible genconfig', when we might expect not to
be making any changes to the remote system.

This change separates out these host configuration tasks into a
config-host.yml file, which is included directly from deploy.yml.

One change in behaviour is that this prevents these tasks from running
during genconfig.

This commit also includes a follow up to the original commit,
I79fcbf1efb02b7187406d3c3fccea6f200bcea69: Perform host configuration
during upgrade

To maintain previous behaviour, and ensure we catch any host
configuration changes, we should perform host configuration during
upgrade.

Change-Id: I001defc75d1f1e6caa9b1e11246abc6ce17c775b
Closes-Bug: #1860161
(cherry picked from commit fdea19a305c0926f4be4c0c5f29e57bdb5a9ee85)
(cherry picked from commit 1d70f509e30688826304e57775eabcd7b1e9afd2)

commit_message:
Add memcached caching

Piggybacking on to the memcached containers that keystone uses for
its token caching we are able to share state between the apache_mod_openidc
instances so that authentications succeed in cases where auth requests
are being routed to more than one keystone container.

Change-Id: Ia978b46f6a6dfc5da8f8ebecb1a3c9fe44948add
(cherry picked from commit beebf1196e38ce76e0a65ff46c2bb58585d8e5bd)

commit_message:
Remove Monasca Log API

Monasca, since the Train release has supported a unified API for both
logs and metrics. The Log API is no longer required.

Change-Id: I5a59a84b00a1770bfaf7257295e82bb5b92df029

commit_message:
Fix hacking min version to 3.0.1

flake8 new release 3.8.0 added new checks and gate pep8
job start failing. hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to
avoid bringing in a new version with new checks.

Though it is fixed in latest hacking but 2.0 and 3.0 has cap for
flake8 as <4.0.0 which mean flake8 new version 3.9.0 can also
break the pep8 job if new check are added.

To avoid similar gate break in future, we need to bump the hacking min
version.

Also removing the hacking and other related dep from lower-constraints file
as theose are blacklisted requirements and does not need to be present
there.

- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014828.html

Change-Id: Icad3221eddcc5f4e3b17f7d11266d938d1ea6201

commit_message:
Add '__version__' attribute

This is recommended - though not mandated - by PEP8 and some other PEPs,
such as PEP396. The 'version_string' attribute is removed from the
'nova.virt' module since this was returning a function rather than a
string and was essentially useless.

Change-Id: I0753ac42a3ebd8dd096774fe005ac17d6fd0e58c
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <stephenfin@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add config option for neutron client retries

Nova can occasionally fail to carry out server actions which require
calls to neutron API if haproxy happens to close a connection after
idle time if an incoming request attempts to re-use the connection
while it is being torn down.

In order to be more resilient to this scenario, we can add a config
option for neutron client to retry requests, similar to our existing
CONF.cinder.http_retries and CONF.glance.num_retries options.

Because we create our neutron client [1] using a keystoneauth1 session
[2], we can set the 'connect_retries' keyword argument to let
keystoneauth1 handle connection retries.

Conflicts:
	nova/conf/neutron.py
NOTE(s10): conflict is due to Id7c2f0b53c8871ff47a836ec4c324c8cce430b79
not being in Queens.

Closes-Bug: #1866937

[1] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/57459c3429ce62975cebd0cd70936785bdf2f3a4/nova/network/neutron.py#L226-L237
[2] https://docs.openstack.org/keystoneauth/latest/api/keystoneauth1.session.html#keystoneauth1.session.Session

Change-Id: Ifb3afb13aff7e103c2e80ade817d0e63b624604a
(cherry picked from commit 0e34ed9733e3f23d162e3e428795807386abf1cb)
(cherry picked from commit 71971c206292232fff389dedbf412d780f0a557a)
(cherry picked from commit a96e7ab83066bee0a13a54070aab988396bae320)
(cherry picked from commit 6bed39cd6e77744ca4bbad9dba3f68c78cdc1ec0)

commit_message:
Fix neutron tests

Test test_handle_trunk_remove_trunk_manager_failure is trying
to connect to tcp:127.0.0.1:6640. This behaviour can be visible
by netcat while test is running. As this is unit test, it should
use mock, not real ovsdb. This patch is fixing this.

$ nc -l -p 6640
{"id":0,"method":"get_schema","params":["Open_vSwitch"]}

Change-Id: I25161913d701e15d127c70d71ac025e4573e81f1

commit_message:
Fix hacking min version to 3.0.1

flake8 new release 3.8.0 added new checks and gate pep8
job start failing. hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to
avoid bringing in a new version with new checks.

Though it is fixed in latest hacking but 2.0 and 3.0 has cap for
flake8 as <4.0.0 which mean flake8 new version 3.9.0 can also
break the pep8 job if new check are added.

To avoid similar gate break in future, we need to bump the hacking min
version.

- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014828.html

Change-Id: I8381a68dfcc59e8dd5167faae1c05d2974db1315

commit_message:
Fix OEM extension loading for different servers

Remove caching and re-using loaded extension objects
as it loaded the same instance for different servers
making it impossible to use it for more than 1
server.

The caching of extension managers is still in place,
consumer of loaded extension object can manage and
reuse the instance as needed.

Change-Id: I7834b49455258f4c3e5690708b23c67d6a361158
Story: 2007669
Task: 39767
(cherry picked from commit 359f2ec2c11cf4e4d2677c2af4ed715e92ce33f3)

commit_message:
Fix OEM extension loading for different servers

Remove caching and re-using loaded extension objects
as it loaded the same instance for different servers
making it impossible to use it for more than 1
server.

The caching of extension managers is still in place,
consumer of loaded extension object can manage and
reuse the instance as needed.

Change-Id: I7834b49455258f4c3e5690708b23c67d6a361158
Story: 2007669
Task: 39767
(cherry picked from commit 359f2ec2c11cf4e4d2677c2af4ed715e92ce33f3)

commit_message:

commit_message:
Remove the unused coding style modules

Python modules related to coding style checks (listed in blacklist.txt in
openstack/requirements repo) are dropped from lower-constraints.txt
as they are not actually used in tests (other than pep8).

more info: https://github.com/openstack/requirements/blob/master/blacklist.txt

Change-Id: Ia68dd55193f7357916be40054f793dc2078a5d8b

`3600` leaving `00` which failed the regex search. We could reverse
the order of the regexs so that longer ones appeared before shorter
ones, but why not just check membership in list?

commit_message:
Pin the python-ibmcclient upper bounds due to six usage

Python-ibmcclient 0.2.0 uses six, which is not installed by default
as it is not necessary for python3 only usage.

This patch pins the upper bounds until the library can be fixed and
a new version released.

Changes:
  Also pinning pycodestyle to cope with pep8 failures.

Change-Id: I06136f3f445b6ee4858697e22e8d63ca3d81c137
(cherry picked from commit f6b9f343581eb430cb339dde09bf97915e2e3a7b)

commit_message:
Enable focal and ussuri as part of the gate tests

Add bionic-ussuri and focal-ussuri (with mysql8 support) bundles.
The func-test-pr is to ensure that a focal LTS image is available for
the focal tests.

Update GSS mirror config so it downloads focal images.

Change-Id: I21e1803b146783a6f149a060605ad48d63a6a692

commit_message:
Update scheduler instance info at confirm resize

When a resize is confirmed the instance does not belong to the source
compute any more. In the past the scheduler instance info is only
updated by the _sync_scheduler_instance_info periodic. This caused that
server boots with anti-affinity did not consider the source host.
But now at the end of the confirm_resize call the compute also updates
the scheduler about the move.

Change-Id: Ic50e72e289b56ac54720ad0b719ceeb32487b8c8
Closes-Bug: #1869050

commit_message:
When adding a cluster node try rescan first

When adding a node it seems to be possible that the cluster is
aware of the node but metadata still needs updating. If this is the
case then running Cluster.add_instance results in an error like

`X is part of the Group Replication group but is not in the metadata.
Please use <Cluster>.rescan() to update the metadata.`

Using rescan to add the instances does seem to work in this case.
So try that first and fall back to running Cluster.add_instance
if rescan fails.

Replacing Cluster.add_instance with Cluster.rescan({'addInstances
is not sufficent as charm can be completely unaware of the peer in
which case the rescan method fails.

Change-Id: I81a3a23df0a702ba39fa7e9292af60f697b6cfe4
Closes-Bug: #1876861

commit_message:
updater: Shuffle suffixes so we don't keep hitting the same failures

When tuning your updater, you often want to try a new config, see how it
changes your metrics, then adjust concurrency up or down depending on
how your container layer is responding.

If your containers haven't been doing well, though, and you've got a
giant backlog of async pendings to work through, updater restarts to
change concurrency previously posed a problem: the updater would walk
the suffix directories in the same order every start-up. So, if you
found a config that was making decent progress for a while but still had
*some* failures, and you wanted to try tweaking settings to see if you
could *reduce* those failures -- you'd likely start getting *all*
failures as it went to retry the failed ones first and all at once. If
you continued trying to tweak configs to get your failures to a
reasonable rate, you'd almost certainly over-correct for these handful 
of overwhelmed DBs and not the overall cluster.

Now, shuffle the suffixes before we walk them.

Change-Id: I3ef34119f0cb563ab405a6517335a24dbaf2b4c3
Closes-Bug: #1878056

commit_message:
Add mode option when creating persistent directories.

Almost every single tripleo service creates a persistent directory. To
simplify the creation, a with_items structure was being used. In which
many times, the mode option was being set. However, that mode option
was not taken into account at the time of creating the file. As a
consequence, the directory was being created with its father directory
rights, instead of the ones being passed in the template.

Change-Id: I215db2bb79029c19ab8c62a7ae8d93cec50fb8dc
Closes-Bug: #1871231
(cherry picked from commit 94bc023390fd34d1a7db4dddb2c92ebe3877b0fb)

commit_message:
builder/buildah: use tenacity to retry failing pushes

There are multiple reasons that can prevent the container image push
command to fail:
- network issue
- remote registry error or rate limit

This patch will use tenacity to retry the push up to 10 times
jittered exponential backoff.

Change-Id: If82bf022e9944ce5a224c611ca16c74ca4cc0771
(cherry picked from commit 1fbea6a972ea1a22f716c418762e63462516bd67)

commit_message:
Enable os_tempest in quickstart-extras-validate playbook

This is needed so os-tempest can also be used in addition to
validate-tempest role to run tempest when quickstart-extras-validate
playbook is used.

Also let's ensure virtualenv package is installed
when using os-tempest  it can be absent when.

Change-Id: I44ab4eff686100966012118ccd9ac016d6c2ee54

commit_message:
Fix errors found by new pycodestyle

pycodestyle 2.6.0 has some new errors, fix them.

Also bumped minimum hacking to 3.0.1 so it pulls in
the correct flake8, etc, libraries.

Added basepython directive in tox.ini since local
'tox -e pep8' runs were using python2 otherwise.

Change-Id: I3a9f7c2df5b68a3bad036121c9b10b1c184d261c

commit_message:
Switch to newer openstackdocstheme and reno versions

Switch to openstackdocstheme 2.1.2 and reno 3.1.0 versions. Using
these versions will allow parallelizing building of documents.

Update Sphinx version as well.

openstackdocstheme renames some variables, so follow the renames. A
couple of variables are also not needed anymore, remove them.

Set openstackdocs_auto_version to not version the documents.
Set openstackdocs_auto_name to use project as name.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/728432
Change-Id: I4e3ae3ceabe125ea459ed4baabf2e98686268e50

commit_message:
Switch to newer openstackdocstheme and reno versions

Switch to openstackdocstheme 2.1.2 and reno 3.1.0 versions. Using
these versions will allow parallelizing building of documents.

Update Sphinx version as well.

openstackdocstheme renames some variables, so follow the renames. A
couple of variables are also not needed anymore, remove them.
Remove duplicated variables.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/728432
Change-Id: Icb604b31150a1ad6c29a9a4a934ed13f8a0b4976

commit_message:
Gate fix: use tempest-horizon 0.2.0 explicitly

tempest-horizon master no longer support python 2.7, but
the tempest job in stable/rocky (and older) runs with python 2.7.
tempest-horizon 0.2.0 is the last release with python 2.7,
so we need to use the version explicitly.

Change-Id: Ia5ae3aa2b024f554eb8c068b9cc271998db6f909
Closes-Bug: #1874171

commit_message:
PowerMax Driver - U4P failover lock not released on exception

During U4P failover, if the initial operation that triggered the
failover hits an exception it can leave the failover lock in place.
Any operations waiting for lock to clear will continue to loop in place.
Added additional lock releases in exception catches and also a maximum
time that the holding operations should wait.

Change-Id: I43319854df9597df791a83cb4c598db0db3caec7
Closes-bug: 1875640

commit_message:
Fix mock.patch.stopall issue with ovsdbapp

After I876919dfc1fa0ae36bd99e3d760e38d207ee6ef3, two test classes
that inherit from both neutron's oslotest-based base classes and
ovsdbapp's unittest-based base class would fail due to
mock.patch.stopall being called twice. This appears to be because
of some special handling in oslotest addCleanup that checks a
private _cleanups variable before adding a cleanup to stopall.
Changing the order of the imports so that neutron can register its
cleanups first seems to fix the issue.

Closes-Bug: #1878708
Change-Id: I5b3812a9765a37b3e66d6c8ca0cb42ee1b7a2b9a

commit_message:
New TEMPEST_VOLUME_REVERT_TO_SNAPSHOT setting

Follow the pattern of the other configuration keys. The new variables
allows tests to enable/disable volume revert tests provided
by cinder-tempest-plugin.

Revert-to-snapshot was introduced in pike, and so the tests.

Change-Id: If137f201c2f646703f5a1ff96e71e48caed63b67

commit_message:
CI: raise DIB jobs memory to 3 GiB

The only reason the current 2 GiB nodes work is because DIB started
removing linux-firmware from its images. Unfortunately, we need this
package on bare metal, and readding it brings to 3 GiB consump

Change-Id: Ic0f2274b29abe7470b835cfc305898643204e1f6

commit_message:
Use flask's builtin methods for test context

In Python 3.8 unittest.mock can't successfully mock Flask.
So we need to use test_request_context instead.

Tests are slightly restructured: assertions are now done on an actual
Response object.

Remove some apparently duplicated lines.

Change-Id: I83f240400295d38fe40d54ab7a8f6442f3981729
Story: 2007596
Task: 39565
(cherry picked from commit 1fea6624b4cdecf9d95de5912e192eb50bbda795)

Testing in:

https://review.opendev.org/728263/
https://review.opendev.org/728272

> Testing in:
 > 
 > https://review.opendev.org/728263/
 > https://review.opendev.org/728272
 > https://review.opendev.org/728270

Unfortunately it would not tests as tox use released constarint not from cloned repo.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2020-05-15 13:56:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> > Testing in:
 > >
 > > https://review.opendev.org/728263/
 > > https://review.opendev.org/728272
 > > https://review.opendev.org/728270
 > 
 > Unfortunately it would not tests as tox use released constarint not
 > from cloned repo.

It does at least partially. I'm currently hunting down the bugs where it fails.

It works here:
https://zuul.opendev.org/t/openstack/build/bd7ce066b0a549f683e2f04e82083598/log/job-output.txt#525

But breaks in PDF build."}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2020-05-15 15:26:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

ok, does this need to be blacklisted as well?'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2020-05-15 15:30:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

No need to black list this, we fixed zuul-jobs and openstack-zuul-jobs bugs that our testing triggered - and now python-novaclient is building correctly with a depends-on this change (failed before).

Depends-On is now working correctly for constraints also for PDF.

Let's wait for the results from nova and cinder whether those are fine as well.

See https://review.opendev.org/#/q/status:open++topic:reno-openstacksdocstheme for the changes I have up.

Let's keep my -1 as WIP, I'll change to +1 once tests ar efine."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2020-05-15 16:10:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2020-05-15 16:11:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

nova and novaclient are green, cinder and oslo.concurrency are passing docs jobs.'}, {'account_id': 14288, 'date': '2020-05-15 16:12:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2020-05-15 16:19:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]

commit_message:
Add a /healthcheck middleware

By default, cinder-api isn't providing a /healthcheck URL, which is
super useful for setting-up monitoring and HAProxy. This patch adds
it by default.

Change-Id: I03a93bf14a5ba159b68bfba15a7f4f26c8200e36

commit_message:
Suppress remaining policy warnings in unit tests

There are few place left in unit tests where policy warnings
are still logged.

- test_policy which is policy file tests and does policy
  initialization without suppressing the warnings.

- test_serversV21. PolicyFixture takes care of policy setup with
  no warning things[1] which is used by test base class[2] but
  test_serversV21 dulicate the policy initialization which leads
  to log warnings for unit tests. We do not need to initialization
  policy again and can reply on PolicyFixture setup.

  From the git history, it was added 7 years ago when no
  Fixture was available so there is no specific reason of re-initializating
  the policy in this test.
  - https://review.opendev.org/#/c/16160/3

[1] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/4b62c90063abc0c1b3e6b564a171e8c1d96cb735/nova/tests/unit/policy_fixture.py#L46
[2] https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/4b62c90063abc0c1b3e6b564a171e8c1d96cb735/nova/test.py#L269

Change-Id: Ieb3f5510437d38bf2a4c8994d76c7f4001a6c9d8
